annotations:
I’m trying to seem strong for my love
 For my family and friends
 But I’m so tired of faking
 ’Cause I’m chained to my bed when they’re gone
 Watching TV alone

Soccer Mommy discusses a lot about their struggles with anxiety from sleep paralysis and deep depression episodes. When struggling with depression, not many people around you always understand it. It is seen as that you are “crazy” and just need to get into a relationship. She hides her struggles because it is easier than having that difficult conservation with people who care about you.

I’m wobbling out on the wire
 And the lights could go out
 With the break of a cable

Managing her mental health is difficult and stressful, as if she is walking a tightrope that doubles as an electrical cord. She has to be wary of the stimuli she takes in., for the smallest occurrence could trigger a new low.

Split open, watching my heart go
 ’Round and around, ’round and around
 Circle the drain, I’m going down

Sophie also mentions sinks/drains in the song “Bloodstream”:

Now a river runs red from my knuckles into the sink

“Bloodstream” touches on her struggles with self harm, which could insinuate that this chorus is also a reference to that and a tendency to enter a cycle of depression, seen by the repeating phrase “round and around.”

The phrase “split open” could be alluding to a feeling of brokenness, vulnerability, or again to self-harm wounds.

And I think there’s a mold in my brain
 Spreading down all the way
 Through my heart and my body
Again, more head-to-toe imagery; in this case, she feels so numb, as if her body is steadily decaying.

I wanna be calm like the soft
 Summer rain on your back
 Like the fall of your shoulders
 But everything just brings me back down
 To the cold hard ground
 And it keeps getting colder
The imagery of these lines starts from her head to her toes, emphasizing the ‘highs’ that she desires and the ‘lows’ she ultimately ends up feeling.

description.plain: “Your Dog” is the first single released off the Soccer Mommy’s 2018 album Clean. The song is about the anger and relief of the singer finally admitting she was being used in an emotionally abusive relationship. The music video, released the same day as the song, shows singer Sophie Allison reveling in her  murder of her partner (played by her boyfriend, band guitarist Julian Powell): she is shown dancing, drawing on his corpse, and rubbing his blood on her face before she eventually cuddles longingly with his dead body.

body.plain: “Your Dog” is the first single released off the Soccer Mommy’s 2018 album Clean. The song is about the anger and relief of the singer finally admitting she was being used in an emotionally abusive relationship. The music video, released the same day as the song, shows singer Sophie Allison reveling in her  murder of her partner (played by her boyfriend, band guitarist Julian Powell): she is shown dancing, drawing on his corpse, and rubbing his blood on her face before she eventually cuddles longingly with his dead body.

annotations: [Verse 1]

The opening lyrics subvert the seminal Stooges hit “I Wanna Be Your Dog,” which features Iggy Pop begging for domination and control by a lover. https://genius.com/The-stooges-i-wanna-be-your-dog-lyrics

I don’t wanna be your fucking dog
 That you drag around

She is expressing frustration over being reduced to an ornament in a relationship.

She recognizes that her partner is beginning to treat her like she is his pet. She is treated like an object that he can show off to his friends, rely on for entertainment, and mistreat without consequence.

Always talk to other people
 Dart my eyes across the room
She sees him talking to other girls, but looks away and pretends that she doesn’t notice

’Cause I don’t wanna be your baby girl
 That you show off to the world and
 When you decide you wanna feel
 Like you’re living something real

she doesn’t want to be used for them to show her off as some kind of prop or trophy. maybe they’re using a relationship with her to show that they’re capable of having one, or as a tether to reality, which “when you decide you want to feel like you’re living something real” suggests. The “baby girl” part makes me think that they’re trying to be extra sweet to her by calling her pet names to try and make up for something. either way, it’s not actually about her so much as its about the image she helps paint

Forehead kisses break my knees and
 Leave me crawling back to you
every time they’re affectionate towards her, it weakens her and makes her go right back to them even though she knows they aren’t treating her right

I don’t wanna be your little pet
 At the edge of every bed
 You sleep in, body stretching out
the person she’s singing about is sleeping in other places with other people but they still keep her close to be able to use again when they’re done

A collar on my neck tied to a pole
 Leave me in the freezing cold

In keeping with the dog imagery, she describes being left with no regard for how she feels, the way someone might tie a dog up and leave it outside. i think she describes being tied up to a pole and left to show that although she’s been left behind, they have her tied up to use again the next time they want to. they haven’t let her go entirely because they want access to her and intend to use her again. The specificity of describing the cold as “freezing” makes you that it’s even more brutal.

I want a love that lets me breathe
 I’ve been choking on your leash
She wants a lover who isn’t abusive. She has been held back so much from the relationship or  “leash” that it is choking her the way it would choke a dog.

I’m not a prop for you to use
 When you’re lonely or confused

People use their pets to get attention or a reaction in social situations. She feels as if the subject of the song is using her when he decides he wants a lover. He is either showing her off just so everyone knows he is with someone, or just using her for physical contact. Or both!
Guess I’ll curl up on the couch
Curling up on couches is decidedly dog-like behavior.

annotations: Bullet in a shotgun
Shotguns fire shot or slugs, not bullets. This is probably not an intentional error, but it might be interesting to consider nonetheless.

Whenever you want me I’ll be around
 I’m a bullet in a shotgun waiting to sound
Just as a bullet sits and waits for someone to unleash its deadly potential, she sits with the large, unruly, and confusing feelings that accompany the early stages of a new relationship.

Cold beer and ice cream is all we keep
 The only things we really need

I don’t drink beer very much any more. I do love it, it’s just trying to cut down on drinking a loaf of bread. But, so ice cream? I really love ice cream and there’s lots of flavors that I love there. I don’t like triple chocolate type of stuff. I’m big on, there’s this Jeni’s flavor. I worked at Jeni’s. There’s this one that’s brown butter almond brittle, that one is absolutely amazing. I love a good mint chocolate chip.
I like a lot of vanilla-based ones, I feel like, because then you can get chocolate and stuff in and it’s not too much. I think my most controversial thing is that I think that strawberry ice cream is disgusting. I think fruit ice cream in general, it should just be a sorbet. I don’t know why there is milk in there with it.
Especially strawberry. That’s the same thing with, I didn’t like milk growing up. I would only have chocolate milk. People who’d have strawberry milk, I was like, “Oh my god, that’s horrible. That’s like just a chemical mixed in with your milk.” I just think that kind of stuff is gross.
I think my favorite beer, I’ll make this one faster. We really like Coors, that’s a solid. But I like light ones, like Bud, Coors. If we’re going to like an actual place to buy it, we love Beerlao, which is a Lao beer, I guess it’s a lager. Just stuff like that. Lots of Japanese beer. Lagers are really good.

– Soccer Mommy, 88Nine Radio Milwaukee
Coffee and menthol on your breath
A common practice to covering up the smell of cigarettes is drinking coffee. The menthol being described is probably the scent and flavor of menthol cigarettes.

Uppers and my heart never meshed
 I hated coming down
 But this feels the same without the bad things
“Uppers” is a term used to describe stimulant drugs, such as cocaine and ecstasy (or in more mild cases, caffeine such as referenced in the line before).

body.plain:
“​yellow is the color of her eyes” is the second preview of Soccer Mommy’s second album, color theory.

The song was inspired by the terminal illness that Sophie Allison’s mother has been suffering with since Allison was a pre-teen. The color yellow is in fact a sign of physical sickness.

songs.title: Yellow is the color of her eyes (demo)
songs.title_with_featured: Yellow is the color of her eyes (demo)

annotations:
The tiny lie I told to myself is making me hollow
 I’ve been choking up truths that I couldn’t swallow

The lie that she tells herself could be her pretending that her mother is healthy and not sick so she doesn’t have to face the pain of realizing a loved one could soon pass. This lie only make her feel worse (as bottling up emotions often does), but when she tries to accept the truth (that her mother is dying), it’s too difficult. This puts her in a rough place because either way she’s left feeling empty (as a result of lies or grief).
I’ll know the day when it comes

This line further illustrates Allison’s deep connection with her mother. She doesn’t need someone to tell her when her mother dies; she’ll already know when it’s happened because she will have felt a part of her own soul die.

And I could lie
 But it’s never made me feel good inside
She could lie to herself and say that her mother will be alright, but she knows that’s not true and that only makes things worse

I’m thinking of her from over the ocean
 See her face in the waves, her body is floating
 And in her eyes, like clementines, I know that she’s fading
 And the light of the sun is only a daydream

Soccer Mommy explained in an interview that this song is about her mother who has an illness, and how she would think about her mom while touring. She felt like she was losing time with her mom as she travelled around the world, as shown here.

I’m still so blue
 I can’t erase the hue, it’s just colored over

This part of the song plays into the title of the album, color theory, along with the colors of the album cover. (This makes sense as it’s the ending song on the album).

Color theory is basically the practice of combining colors to make new hues. In the example for the album, there are two colors involved: yellow (happiness) and blue (sadness). She is trying to mask her blue with the yellow to cope with her reality of her mom being sick (this is referenced in the bio of this song’s music video on YouTube). This form of coping through lies and denial isn’t working, which is why she says “I can’t erase the hue, it’s just colored over.” She isn’t happy, nothing is working. The blue is more apparent than the yellow, so she finally has to accept the reality of her mom’s situation.

The bright August sun feels like yellow
 And the white of her eyes is so yellow

These two lines create a juxtaposition where in the first line, the colour yellow is being used to describe the sun, relating the colour to a happy or calm feeling, But in the second line, the colour is used to describe the white of someone’s eyes, something that is a sign of an illness or a disease.
I’ll feel the cold as they put out my sun

The contrast between the blue that is associated with sadness and the happiness (yellow) that her mother brings her emphasises the pain she would feel if her mother passed away. Additionally, the use of ‘They put out my sun’ is a reference to the saying that ‘You are the sun in my sky’ showing the importance that her mother has in life.
You’ll still be deep in the ground when it’s done
She knows her mother is going to die and she’s trying to accept the fact that loving her isn’t enough to keep her alive.

description.plain: The eighth track off Soccer Mommy’s Clean (2018), “Scorpio Rising” serves as a climactic realization that the singer will lose her love to another, and it will be her fault. Stereo Gum described it as a song that begins “deceptively basic… [until] it starts to unfurl into this story about relinquishing a love you want badly but know you cannot maintain” and pointed out that it is “resigned and sad, yes, but it isn’t bitter.”

body.plain: The eighth track off Soccer Mommy’s Clean (2018), “Scorpio Rising” serves as a climactic realization that the singer will lose her love to another, and it will be her fault. Stereo Gum described it as a song that begins “deceptively basic… [until] it starts to unfurl into this story about relinquishing a love you want badly but know you cannot maintain” and pointed out that it is “resigned and sad, yes, but it isn’t bitter.”

annotations:
You want warmth and I’m somethin’ colder
 I’m putting your hands to her heart

With this line, Sophia states the overall message of “Scorpio Rising”: That she believes herself to be driving her lover away by being too icy. The imagery of “putting your hands to her heart” is gentle, rather than firey; she’s not shoving him away, not explicitly pushing, but gently moving him.

The imagery of her as cold connects neatly back to “Your Dog”’s image of her as a dog in the freezing cold, and contrasts sharply with the song’s earlier mention of a “southern summer”.
The tab don’t pop too hard

If the other girl is like a Coca-Cola, getting to know her (like opening a can of Coke) isn’t difficult, while the narrator is distant, unlike the new girl. The next lines reinforce this, the singer is too boring (“playing cards”) and isn’t what he wants (“warmth” vs “colder”).

Sophie uses imagery around pouring a drink in an earlier song on the same album, Flaw, in each case using a drink to distract from heartbreak. This motif implies the two songs may be about the same situation; though they may actually be written about different interactions, they thematically fit together as two songs about losing a love and believing it to be your fault.

’Cause you’re made from the stars
 That we watched from your car

In literature, the stars symbolize fate (as in “star-crossed lovers”), which is a main theme of this song. This line sets up one of the implicit conflicts of the narrative: the protagonist is at once pulled away from her love interest by fate (“scorpio rising”), but she also feels it a stroke of fate itself that she is so drawn to him.

In both cases, she feels helpless, at the mercy of supernatural forces outside of her control.
I watch from my drink as you look her over
This is some cool wordplay as she just mentioned Coca-Cola and now she mentions “my drink” that she is taking a break from enjoying to see her object of admiration with someone else.
Oh she’s bubbly and sweet like a Coca-Cola
Coca-Cola is a soft drink that is carbonated and has a good amount of sugar, hence “bubbly and sweet”

And I’m just a victim of changing planets
 My Scorpio rising and my parents

To those who believe in astrology, planetary alignments hold major significance to the way a person perceives her circumstances. Soccer Mommy herself is a Gemini, and Gemini in Scorpio rising is allegedly prone to “[not being] easily tamed” .

This sentiment is strongly present throughout the album, with her affair with someone already engaged as explored in this track and Still Clean, or her desire to break hearts in Cool.

It’s a bite of the apple, the touch of your lips
 I’m stuck in the bathroom and sick over it

A reference to the biblical story of the Garden of Eden, where the apple represents temptation. By giving in to the temptation- representative of “original sin”- to have a one-night stand with someone who’s already taken, she’s then doomed to regret it.
Ignored all the missed calls from your mother
There are a lot lyrics that talk about meeting up after dark and ignoring your parents, suggesting that maybe this was a relationship that took place when she was younger.
In your car with the backseat, southern summer

While she wrote most of her songs while she was at college in New York, she talks about a “southern summer”, perhaps referencing her hometown of Nashville, Tennessee – meaning that maybe this song is about a relationship from her past.
Now you want to start
New beginnings indicate that old relationships must come to and end. Without explicitly stating it, she realizes that her relationship is also coming to an end.
